{
  "texts": [
    "Precision diagnostics-companion diagnostics (CDx) and complementary diagnostics (cDx) These are in-vitro diagnostic or medical devices for deciding on medicinal product use that: (i) identify patients most likely/unlikely to benefit; (ii) identify patients likely to be at high risk of serious side effects; and/or, (iii) monitor patient response to enable treatment tuning to optimise safety and/or effectiveness [59] [60] [61] [62].",
    "CDx are, if applicable, obligatory for the prescription of the drug, whereas cDx provides optional additional information (e.g.",
    "on enhanced benefits in subgroups) 59 (Fig. 1).",
    "Currently most c/CDx are chemical, genomic biomarkers and immunoassays 59, 63.",
    "In the US, the approval of the drug and c/CDx are assessed by the FDA, enabling coordinated approval 42."
  ]
}